Class Function<T>

Direct Known Subclasses:
Js
public abstract class Function<T>
extends Var<JsFunction<T>>

A normal class extended concretely to define a function object, resembling function definition in JavaScript.

Note that its enclosed classes and members except for function(Object, Call) are all opaque. Its subclasses and their members must be normal.

Author:
J.J.Liu (Jianjun Liu) at http://www.jscripter.org

Method Detail

function

protected abstract T function(java.lang.Object jsthis,
                              Function.Call<T> callee)

An abstract method to be concretely overridden to define the body of the function of the current function object.

The concrete overridden of this method is used to define the function body of the current function object. Re-compilers use the body of the overridden method to define the actual function of the current function object.

Parameters:
jsthis - The scope object.
callee - The function calling this function.
Returns:
The return value of the function.
Since:
1.0

typeof

public final java.lang.String typeof()

An opaque method to return a string indicating the data-type of the function of the current function object.

Simulating the JavaScript typeof operator and typeof() function, this invocation evaluates to "number", "string", or "boolean" if the current instance is a number, string, or boolean value. It evaluates to "object" for objects, arrays. It evaluates to "function" for function instance and to "undefined" if the current instance is undefined.

Overrides:
typeof in class Var<JsFunction<T>>
Returns:
A string indicating the data-type of the function of the current function object.
Since:
1.0
See Also:
valueOf(), undefined()
JavaScript:
Re-compilers must convert this instance invocation into the JavaScript expression: 
typeof f
where f is the function of the current function object instance of the invocation.

valueOf

public final JsFunction<T> valueOf()

An opaque method to return the primitive value associated with the function of the current function object, if there is one.

This invocation simply returns the function of the current function object, since there is no primitive value for a function.
